CM_ SG_ 2147491587 DBW_OverheatPreventMode\ \ "If the tires are rolling, the steady-state steering torque is relatively low\ \ compared to the not-moving case. If the vehicle speed is zero (tires arent rolling)\ \ then holding a constant steering angle requires the EPS motor to fight the spring\ \ force of the rubber on the pavement. In addition, the EPS system will have to\ \ apply this high torque continuously to prevent the steering wheel from springing\ \ back to the same angle as the rubber on the pavement. This high-torque for an\ \ extended period of time is not something the EPS system would encounter with\ \ a human driver because a human would release the steering wheel at 0mph. 

\ To better replicate the behavior of a human driver in this situation, if the vehicle\ \ speed is zero and the AKit steering request has not changed for more than 10\ \ seconds then the DBW will set this flag to indicate that it has zeroed out the\ \ steering torque request (though autonomous control may still be enabled). As\ \ soon as the AKit steering request changes by a si";
CM_ SG_ 2147491587 DBW_SteeringOverheatWarning\ \ "This flag indicates the power steering motor is getting hot due to recent\ \ maneuvers commanded by the autonomous system (most likely lots of steering maneuvers\ \ at zero vehicle speed). Autonomous control and full steering torque will be\ \ allowed for some time, but eventually the power steering motor will derate itself.\ \ If this flag sets, the autonomous system needs to stop commanding the steering\ \ wheel to turn while at 0mph vehicle speed.";

CM_ SG_ 2147495682 AKit_AccelPcntTorqueReq "Used when AKit_AccelReqType\ \ = 1. This mode allows the AKit to request a constant torque value and let the\ \ DBW system adjust the pedal position to meet that torque. 

This value is\ \ in % of a fixed reference value. This reference value depends only on the type\ \ of vehicle.

Note that the reference value is the same in the braking and\ \ AccelPdl control logic. Because any given vehicle"s braking system is usually\ \ more powerful than it"s acceleration system (powertrain), the DBW system will\ \ typically reach the max pedal position when only roughly 50% accel torque is\ \ requested, again depending on the make/model of the vehicle.

100% reference\ \ values for each vehicle platform=
Chrylser Pacifica= 100% = 9.8 m/s^2 acceleration\ \ on flat ground at curb weight.
Volvo VNR=\t 100% = 9.8 m/s^2 acceleration\ \ on flat ground at curb weight.
Toyota Prius=\t 100% = 6.0 m/s^2 acceleration\ \ on flat ground at curb weight.

ROS Attribute= torque_cmd
";

Both must be 2 because speed control will use both the gas and brake (although\ \ a test engineer can leave one of those 2 actuators in manual mode by setting\ \ it"s ***EnbReq flag to zero, just like in other ***ReqType modes).


ROS\ \ Attribute= speed_cmd
";
CM_ SG_ 2147495682 AKit_SpeedModeRoadSlope "positive\ \ = vehicle facing uphill. Used to adjust the torque requested to meet a given\ \ speed (steeper slope requires more torque to hold a constant speed). If this\ \ signal is not available, you can send a constant value of zero and speed control\ \ will still function but the speed controller will have greater error on sloped\ \ surfaces. If internally calibrated to do so, the DBW may also use its own estimate\ \ of road slope IFF the AKit is sending exactly 0 for this signal.

The steepest\ \ grades in the world are 21 degrees, so this scaling will encompass all real-world\ \ roads.

If vehicle is traveling downhill in reverse (facing uphill), this\ \ should still be a positive value. the DBW will compensate for PRND direction.
\ 

ROS Attribute= road_slope
";

CM_ SG_ 2147491587 DBW_OverheatPreventMode\ \ "If the tires are rolling, the steady-state steering torque is relatively low\ \ compared to the not-moving case. In addition, the EPS system will have to\ \ apply this high torque continuously to prevent the steering wheel from springing\ \ back to the same angle as the rubber on the pavement. This high-torque for an\ \ extended period of time is not something the EPS system would encounter with\ \ a human driver because a human would release the steering wheel at 0mph. 

\ To better replicate the behavior of a human driver in this situation, if the vehicle\ \ speed is zero and the AKit steering request has not changed for more than 10\ \ seconds then the DBW will set this flag to indicate that it has zeroed out the\ \ steering torque request (though autonomous control may still be enabled). As\ \ soon as the AKit steering request changes by a si";

CM_ SG_ 2147495682 AKit_AccelPcntTorqueReq "Used when AKit_AccelReqType\ \ = 1. This mode allows the AKit to request a constant torque value and let the\ \ DBW system adjust the pedal position to meet that torque. 

This value is\ \ in % of a fixed reference value. This reference value depends only on the type\ \ of vehicle.

Note that the reference value is the same in the braking and\ \ AccelPdl control logic. Because any given vehicle"s braking system is usually\ \ more powerful than it"s acceleration system (powertrain), the DBW system will\ \ typically reach the max pedal position when only roughly 50% accel torque is\ \ requested, again depending on the make/model of the vehicle.

100% reference\ \ values for each vehicle platform=
Chrylser Pacifica= 100% = 9.8 m/s^2 acceleration\ \ on flat ground at curb weight.
Volvo VNR=\t 100% = 9.8 m/s^2 acceleration\ \ on flat ground at curb weight.
Toyota Prius=\t 100% = 6.0 m/s^2 acceleration\ \ on flat ground at curb weight.

ROS Attribute= torque_cmd

CM_ SG_ 2147495682 AKit_SpeedModeRoadSlope "positive\ \ = vehicle facing uphill. Used to adjust the torque requested to meet a given\ \ speed (steeper slope requires more torque to hold a constant speed). If this\ \ signal is not available, you can send a constant value of zero and speed control\ \ will still function but the speed controller will have greater error on sloped\ \ surfaces. If internally calibrated to do so, the DBW may also use its own estimate\ \ of road slope IFF the AKit is sending exactly 0 for this signal.

The steepest\ \ grades in the world are 21 degrees, so this scaling will encompass all real-world\ \ roads.

If vehicle is traveling downhill in reverse (facing uphill), this\ \ should still be a positive value. the DBW will compensate for PRND direction.
\ 

ROS Attribute= road_slope

CM_ SG_ 2147491587 DBW_OverheatPreventMode\ \ "If the tires are rolling, the steady-state steering torque is relatively low\ \ compared to the not-moving case. If the vehicle speed is zero (tires arent rolling)\ \ then holding a constant steering angle requires the EPS motor to fight the spring\ \ force of the rubber on the pavement. In addition, the EPS system will have to\ \ apply this high torque continuously to prevent the steering wheel from springing\ \ back to the same angle as the rubber on the pavement. This high-torque for an\ \ extended period of time is not something the EPS system would encounter with\ \ a human driver because a human would release the steering wheel at 0mph. 

\ To better replicate the behavior of a human driver in this situation, if the vehicle\ \ speed is zero and the AKit steering request has not changed for more than 10\ \ seconds then the DBW will set this flag to indicate that it has zeroed out the\ \ steering torque request (though autonomous control may still be enabled). As\ \ soon as the AKit steering request changes by a si";
CM_ SG_ 2147491587 DBW_SteeringOverheatWarning\ \ "This flag indicates the power steering motor is getting hot due to recent\ \ maneuvers commanded by the autonomous system (most likely lots of steering maneuvers\ \ at zero vehicle speed). Autonomous control and full steering torque will be\ \ allowed for some time, but eventually the power steering motor will derate itself.\ \ If this flag sets, the autonomous system needs to stop commanding the steering\ \ wheel to turn while at 0mph vehicle speed.";

CM_ SG_ 2147495682 AKit_AccelPcntTorqueReq "Used when AKit_AccelReqType\ \ = 1. This mode allows the AKit to request a constant torque value and let the\ \ DBW system adjust the pedal position to meet that torque.

Note that the reference value is the same in the braking and\ \ AccelPdl control logic. 100% reference\ \ values for each vehicle platform=
Chrylser Pacifica= 100% = 9.8 m/s^2 acceleration\ \ on flat ground at curb weight.
Volvo VNR=\t 100% = 9.8 m/s^2 acceleration\ \ on flat ground at curb weight.

CM_ SG_ 2147495682 AKit_SpeedModeRoadSlope "positive\ \ = vehicle facing uphill. Used to adjust the torque requested to meet a given\ \ speed (steeper slope requires more torque to hold a constant speed). If this\ \ signal is not available, you can send a constant value of zero and speed control\ \ will still function but the speed controller will have greater error on sloped\ \ surfaces. If internally calibrated to do so, the DBW may also use its own estimate\ \ of road slope IFF the AKit is sending exactly 0 for this signal.

The steepest\ \ grades in the world are 21 degrees, so this scaling will encompass all real-world\ \ roads.

If vehicle is traveling downhill in reverse (facing uphill), this\ \ should still be a positive value. the DBW will compensate for PRND direction.
\ 

ROS Attribute= road_slope

CM_ SG_ 2147491587 DBW_OverheatPreventMode\ \ "If the tires are rolling, the steady-state steering torque is relatively low\ \ compared to the not-moving case. If the vehicle speed is zero (tires arent rolling)\ \ then holding a constant steering angle requires the EPS motor to fight the spring\ \ force of the rubber on the pavement. In addition, the EPS system will have to\ \ apply this high torque continuously to prevent the steering wheel from springing\ \ back to the same angle as the rubber on the pavement. This high-torque for an\ \ extended period of time is not something the EPS system would encounter with\ \ a human driver because a human would release the steering wheel at 0mph. 

\ To better replicate the behavior of a human driver in this situation, if the vehicle\ \ speed is zero and the AKit steering request has not changed for more than 10\ \ seconds then the DBW will set this flag to indicate that it has zeroed out the\ \ steering torque request (though autonomous control may still be enabled). As\ \ soon as the AKit steering request changes by a si";
CM_ SG_ 2147491587 DBW_SteeringOverheatWarning\ \ "This flag indicates the power steering motor is getting hot due to recent\ \ maneuvers commanded by the autonomous system (most likely lots of steering maneuvers\ \ at zero vehicle speed). Autonomous control and full steering torque will be\ \ allowed for some time, but eventually the power steering motor will derate itself.\ \ If this flag sets, the autonomous system needs to stop commanding the steering\ \ wheel to turn while at 0mph vehicle speed.";
